The goal of this project is to apply statistical techniques to analyze and predict outcomes using two datasets. The first part focuses on linear regression with a continuous target variable, while the second part explores Generalized Linear Models (GLM) for more complex predictive tasks involving binary variables.

For the linear regression section, a dataset containing life expectancy and other socio-economic indicators for 217 countries will be used to study and understand the relationship between the variables and create a model with robust predictive capabilities.

The second section employs GLM to analyze data from a telecommunications company. The task is to predict whether a customer will make a purchase in the following month. This involves handling binary outcomes, preparing the dataset effectively, and ensuring accurate predictions through appropriate modeling and evaluation techniques.

Only the essential code snippets are presented in this report for clarity and brevity. For the complete code and implementation details, please refer to the accompanying RMarkdown file.

LINEAR REGRESSION

Life expectancy is a critical indicator of a countryâs overall health and socioeconomic development. This project aims to build a linear regression model to predict the life expectancy based on various socio-economic and health-related factors, including GDP per capita, infant mortality rate, fertility rate, access to electricity, and urban population.

countries <- read.csv("D:/1.Universidad/Predictive modeling/Countries.csv")

This dataset was obtained through the World Bank API using a Jupyter Notebook, and the code used for its creation is available in the âApi_Predictive_modeling.ipynbâ file. The dataset was created by selecting the variables considered relevant and appropriate for the objectives of this project for the year 2021. The variables are:

  • iso2code: The two-letter country code used to identify each country.
  • Name : Name of the country.
  • Population: The total population of the country in 2021.
  • Infant_mortality: The infant mortality rate (number of infant deaths per 1,000 live births).
  • Expend_health: Current health expenditure per capita (current US$).
  • GPD_capita: GDP per capita (current US$).
  • Fertility_rate: The average number of children born per woman.
  • Urban_Population: The percentage of the population living in urban areas.
  • Density: The population density, measured as people per square kilometer.
  • Drinking_water: The percentage of the population using at least basic drinking water services.
  • Access_electricity: The percentage of the population with access to electricity.
  • Internet: The percentage of the population using the internet.
  • Unemployment: The unemployment rate, measured as a percentage of the labor force.
  • CO2: Total carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions.
  • Life_expectancy: Life expectancy at birth. Target variable.

When addressing missing values, simple imputation using the median often appears to be a suitable option, particularly for variables with a large number of outliers, as shown in the boxplots. The median is robust to outliers and provides a central tendency measure that avoids the influence of extreme values.

However, imputing with the median has a drawback because it introduces a constant value for missing entries, which can reduce the correlations between variables. This loss of representativeness can weaken the datasetâs ability to capture real-world relationships among variables.

An alternative approach is to impute missing values using a regression model. This method predicts missing values based on the most related variables, potentially maintaining stronger correlations and a more realistic representation of the data. Both options will be considered depending on the variableâs characteristics and their importance in the predictive models.

Preprocessing

With all the insights gained from the exploratory data analysis, preprocessing decisions will now be applied systematically using a pipeline approach. A pipeline ensures consistency and reproducibility, as it automates sequential data transformations, minimizes manual intervention, and reduces the likelihood of errors. Moreover, this approach ensures that the same preprocessing steps are applied consistently to both the training and test datasets, avoiding data leakage and ensuring fair model evaluation.

The steps are:

  1. Impute Missing Values:

    • Median Imputation: Variables like Fertility_rateand Urban_Population are imputed using the median because they have minimal missing values and are not strongly correlated with other variables.
    • Regression Imputation: Missing values in key variables are imputed using regression models, which predict missing values based on the most relevant predictors.
      • Internet is imputed using Access_electricity and Fertility_rate.
      • Drinking_water is imputed using Internet.
      • GDP_capita is imputed using Population, Urban_Population, Internet, Drinking_water, and CO2.
      • Unemployment is imputed using GDP_capita.
      • Infant_mortality is imputed using Drinking_water, Internet, Access_electricity, and Fertility_rate.

  2. Remove Unwanted Columns: Columns CO2 and Expend_health are removed due to high collinearity with other variables (Population and GDP_capita, respectively). Removing these ensures the model focuses on less redundant predictors.

  3. Final Clean-Up: After the imputation process, the pipeline ensures no remaining missing values by applying median imputation as a fallback for numeric variables.

impute_with_model <- function(data, variable, formula) {
  
  model <- lm(as.formula(formula), data = data, na.action = na.exclude)
  
  data[[variable]][is.na(data[[variable]])] <- predict(model, newdata = data[is.na(data[[variable]]), ])
  
  return(data)
}

impute_median <- function(data, columns) {
  data %>%
    dplyr::mutate(across(
      .cols = all_of(columns),
      .fns = ~ ifelse(is.na(.), median(., na.rm = TRUE), .)
    ))
}

remove_unwanted_columns <- function(data) {
  data %>% dplyr::select(-c(CO2, Expend_health))
}
preprocess_data <- function(data) {
  data <- impute_median(data, c("Fertility_rate", "Urban_Population"))
  
  data <- impute_with_model(data, "Internet", "Internet ~  Access_electricity + Fertility_rate")

  data <- impute_with_model(data, "Drinking_water", "Drinking_water ~  Internet  ")
  
  data <- impute_with_model(data, "GDP_capita", "GDP_capita ~ Population + Urban_Population + Internet + Drinking_water + CO2")
  
  data <- impute_with_model(data, "Unemployment", "Unemployment ~ GDP_capita   ")
  
  data <- impute_with_model(data, "Infant_mortality", "Infant_mortality ~ Drinking_water + Internet + Access_electricity  + Fertility_rate ")
  
  data <- remove_unwanted_columns(data)
  
  data <- data %>%
    dplyr::mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ ifelse(is.na(.), median(., na.rm = TRUE), .)))
  
  return(data)
}

countries_train2 = preprocess_data(countries_train)

Predictive analysis

The next step involves transitioning from exploratory data analysis to predictive modeling. In this phase, various regression models and techniques will be explored to identify the best approach for predicting Life_expectancy. The focus is not only on achieving high predictive accuracy but also on ensuring that the model generalizes well to unseen data, avoiding overfitting. Techniques such as feature selection and LASSO regression will be applied to address multicollinearity and improve model performance. The goal is to strike a balance between simplicity and predictive power, ensuring the model is interpretable and reliable.

In this analysis, the adjusted \(R^2\) will be prioritized over the regular \(R^2\) for model evaluation. While the regular \(R^2\) increases with the addition of predictors regardless of their relevance, the adjusted \(R^2\) penalizes the inclusion of non-informative variables, providing a more accurate measure of the modelâs explanatory power when multiple predictors are used.

Models by hand

The first step in the predictive analysis involves exploring models manually, leveraging the insights gained from the exploratory data analysis.

Evaluation of the models will focus on examining both the \(R^2\) adjusted values for the training and test datasets, as well as the statistical significance of the predictors. Additionally, meaningful diagnostic plots and visualizations will be presented to comprehensively assess the modelsâ performance and understand their behaviour.

Now that the final model has been selected, it is crucial to verify whether the necessary assumptions for linear regression have been met. These assumptions include the normality of residuals, homoscedasticity (constant variance of residuals), independence of residuals, and linearity of relationships between predictors and the target variable. To assess these conditions, diagnostic plots were generated and statistical tests were performed:

  • Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test: This test evaluates whether the residuals follow a normal distribution.
  • Breusch-Pagan Test: This test checks for homoscedasticity, ensuring that the variance of the residuals remains constant across fitted values.

  • Residuals vs.Â Fitted Plot: This plot shows no clear patterns, indicating that the assumption of linearity between the predictors and the response variable is satisfied. Additionally, the spread of residuals appears relatively consistent, supporting homoscedasticity.

  • Q-Q Plot: The points in the Q-Q plot mostly align with the diagonal line, suggesting that the residuals follow a normal distribution.

  • Scale-Location Plot: The residuals exhibit a fairly consistent spread across fitted values, further confirming the assumption of homoscedasticity.

These high VIF values confirm substantial multicollinearity between Internet, its interaction term, and other predictors. Multicollinearity inflates the standard errors of coefficients, reduces the interpretability of the model, and may compromise the stability of the regression results.

Given these findings, LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator) regression will be applied to address multicollinearity and enhance model robustness. LASSO is particularly effective in shrinking or eliminating coefficients of less important variables, thereby selecting the most relevant predictors while mitigating the effects of multicollinearity.

LASSO

LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator) is a regression technique that performs variable selection and regularization to enhance the predictive accuracy and interpretability of statistical models. It works by adding a penalty term to the ordinary least squares (OLS) loss function, proportional to the absolute values of the regression coefficients.

This penalty causes some coefficients to shrink towards zero, effectively excluding less important predictors from the model. By doing so, LASSO is particularly effective in addressing multicollinearity among predictors and simplifying models.

This R code implements a LASSO regression model, it employs a workflow that includes data preprocessing (normalization of numeric predictors and removal of zero-variance predictors) and hyperparameter tuning for the regularization penalty. Cross-validation is conducted with 10 folds to evaluate the modelâs performance across a grid of 20 penalty values using metrics such as RMSE and R-squared. The best penalty value is selected based on the lowest RMSE, and the final model is trained using this optimal configuration.

lasso_spec <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = 1) %>%
  set_engine("glmnet") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

recipe <- recipe(Life_expectancy ~ ., data = countries_train2) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%  
  step_zv(all_predictors()) 

workflow_lasso <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(lasso_spec) %>%
  add_recipe(recipe)

set.seed(100452928)
cv_folds <- vfold_cv(countries_train2, v = 10)
metrics <- yardstick::metric_set(yardstick::rmse, yardstick::rsq)

lasso_results <- tune_grid(
  workflow_lasso,
  resamples = cv_folds,
  grid = 20,  
  metrics = metrics  
)
best_lasso <- select_best(lasso_results, "rmse")
final_lasso <- finalize_workflow(workflow_lasso, best_lasso)

lasso_fit <- fit(final_lasso, data = countries_train2)

The LASSO model demonstrates excellent performance on the test set, as indicated by the following metrics: - \(R^2_{test} = 0.8629\). This value shows that the LASSO model explains 86.29% of the variability in the test set, which reflects strong predictive power.

A noteworthy observation is that the \(R^2_{test}\) is slightly higher than the \(R^2_{train}\). While this is unusual, it does not indicate overfitting. Overfitting would typically manifest as significantly better performance on the training set compared to the test set, which is not the case here. Possible reasons for this observation include:

  • Random Variability: The test set might coincidentally align better with the patterns captured by the model, resulting in a higher \(R^2_{test}\)

  • Differences in Variance: The test set may have lower variability in the target variable, making it easier for the model to achieve a higher \(R^2_{test}\)

The adjusted \(R^2\) for LASSO (0.8629) is higher than that of the linear model (0.80). While the sign and magnitude of LASSO coefficients still indicate the direction and relative importance of predictors, their exact values are influenced by the penalty term, making them less reliable for quantifying precise impacts.

Best feature selection

The final approach to be tested in this analysis is best feature selection. This method involves identifying and selecting the most relevant predictors based on their contribution to the modelâs performance. By systematically evaluating subsets of predictors, the goal is to achieve a balance between model complexity and predictive accuracy.

The model begins by fitting a full multiple linear regression to predict Life_expectancy based on all available predictors in the training dataset. It then applies a stepwise selection process using the stepAIC function to refine the model. This method iteratively adds or removes predictors based on the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), aiming to balance model fit and complexity. By choosing the combination of predictors that minimizes AIC, the stepwise approach ensures a more parsimonious model while avoiding overfitting. The resulting model retains only the most relevant variables for predicting Life_expectancy.

full_model <- lm(
  Life_expectancy ~ .,
  data = countries_train2  
)

stepwise_model <- stepAIC(full_model, direction = "both", trace = F)

Benchmark Model

A benchmark model is a simple, baseline model used to compare against a more complex model to evaluate its performance. It provides a reference point to determine if the more advanced model adds value. For this case, we chose a benchmark that predicts the mean of the dependent variable. This approach is commonly used because it is straightforward, easy to implement, and provides a clear baseline to evaluate whether the stepwise regression model significantly improves prediction accuracy over simply predicting the average.

mean_life_expectancy <- mean(countries_train2$Life_expectancy)

benchmark_pred <- rep(mean(real), n)

The table compares the performance metrics of the benchmark model. The \(R^2\) value is 0.0000, which is expected for a benchmark model based on predicting the mean of the dependent variable. This occurs because the benchmark model does not explain any variability beyond the mean, resulting in \(SSE = SST\). The Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) values indicate the average prediction errors, which are expected to be relatively high given the simplicity of the benchmark model. This baseline is useful to demonstrate whether the stepwise regression model significantly improves prediction performance.

Comparision between models and conclusions

The benchmark model, which predicts the mean life expectancy for all countries, serves as a simple baseline for comparison. While it provides a basic reference point, it fails to capture any of the underlying relationships between life expectancy and other variables.

An initial manually constructed model improved upon the benchmark by incorporating relevant predictors. However, this model exhibited significant multicollinearity which can inflate variance and lead to unreliable coefficient estimates. Multicollinearity makes it difficult to discern the individual effect of each predictor, undermining the modelâs interpretability and stability.

To mitigate multicollinearity and enhance predictive performance, we applied LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator) regression. This approach improved the modelâs predictive accuracy compared to the manual model. However, the interpretability of the LASSO model decreased because the regularization process can obscure the impact of individual predictors, especially when coefficients are shrunk or eliminated entirely.

Finally, we employed stepwise feature selection to build a model that maintains strong predictive power while enhancing interpretability. The resulting model not only achieved better predictive performance than the manual model and was comparable to the LASSO model but also was simpler and easier to interpret by including only the most significant variables and excluding redundant ones.

The dataset is divided into a training set and a test set, with 75% of the data assigned to training and the remaining 25% set aside for testing. To evaluate the correlation between the predictor variables and the target variable, a t-test was used because all the predictor variables are numeric. The t-test is a statistical method that assesses whether there are significant differences in the means of a numeric variable between two groups. In this context, the two groups are defined by the TARGET variable.

The t-test evaluates the null hypothesis that the means of the numeric variable are equal across the two TARGET categories. A low p-value from the t-test indicates that the differences in means are statistically significant, suggesting that the variable might be relevant for predicting the target variable.

The table displays the variables with p-values greater than 0.05, indicating that they do not have a statistically significant relationship with the target variable. As these variables lack meaningful predictive power, they will be excluded during the preprocessing phase to streamline the model and improve its performance.

Based on the analysis of correlations, the following decisions were made to select the most representative variables while removing redundant ones:

Variables with Perfect Correlation (1)

  • Between NUM_POSTPAID_SERVICES and NUM_POSTPAID_LINES, we chose to keep NUM_POSTPAID_SERVICES as it better summarizes postpaid services.

  • Between NUM_LINES_UNKNOWN_TECHNOLOGY and NUM_POSTPAID_LINES,we retainedNUM_POSTPAID_SERVICES`.

  • For NUM_FIXED_POSTPAID_LINES and NUM_FIXED_LINES, we decided to keep NUM_FIXED_LINES because it is a more general variable.

  • Between NUM_FIXED_DEACTIVATIONS and NUM_FIXED_POSTPAID_DEACTIVATIONS, we retained NUM_FIXED_DEACTIVATIONS, which includes all deactivations.

Variables with Very High Correlation (>0.95)

  • Between MONTHLY_MB and MB_TOTAL, we chose to keep MONTHLY_MB as it represents average monthly usage.

  • For TOTAL_POSTPAID_SERVICES and NUM_TOTAL_POSTPAID_LINES, we retained TOTAL_POSTPAID_SERVICES, which includes all services.

  • Between INVOICING_TOTAL_WITHOUT_TAXES and INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES, we kept INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES as it includes taxes and provides a more complete financial perspective.

  • For NUM_CALLS_OWN_NETWORK and SECONDS_INCOMING_CALL_OWN_NETWORK, we decided to retain NUM_CALLS_OWN_NETWORK since a count is easier to interpret than call duration in seconds.

Variables with High Correlation (>0.75)

  • Between TOTAL_BRAND_SERVICES and variables NUM_POSTPAID_LINES, NUM_POSTPAID_SERVICES, and NUM_LINES_UNKNOWN_TECHNOLOGY, we kept TOTAL_BRAND_SERVICES, which represents all services, and removed the others.

  • For SECONDS_OUTGOING_CALL_OWN_NETWORK and SECONDS_CALL_OWN_NETWORK, we retained SECONDS_CALL_OWN_NETWORK as it represents the total call duration.

  • Between NUM_DAYS_ACTIVE and DAYS_FIRST_ACCOUNT, we opted to keep NUM_DAYS_ACTIVE because it better reflects the customerâs active period.

  • For MOBILE_CALL_MINUTES and MOBILE_CALLS, we decided to keep MOBILE_CALLS because a count of calls is easier to interpret.

  • Between KPI_TAXES and INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES, we retained INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES as it represents the total invoiced amount, including taxes.

  • For INVOICING_TERM and both INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES and INVOICING_TOTAL_WITHOUT_TAXES, we chose to retain INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES as it includes taxes.

  • Among NUM_POSTPAID_LINES, NUM_POSTPAID_SERVICES, and NUM_LINES_UNKNOWN_TECHNOLOGY with INVOICING_QUOTA, we decided to keep INVOICING_QUOTA if it is relevant for the analysis while removing the others, which were already considered redundant with TOTAL_BRAND_SERVICES.

Preprocessing

The pipeline performs two main preprocessing tasks. First, it imputes missing values for all numeric variables using their median values. Second, it removes a predefined set of columns that are redundant, highly correlated, or deemed irrelevant for the analysis.

impute_median <- function(data) {
  data %>%
    mutate(across(
      .cols = where(is.numeric), 
      .fns = ~ ifelse(is.na(.), median(., na.rm = TRUE), .) 
    ))
}


remove_unwanted_columns <- function(data) {
  data %>% dplyr::select(-c(
    "NUM_LINES_UNKNOWN_TECHNOLOGY", 
    "NUM_FIXED_POSTPAID_LINES", 
    "NUM_FIXED_POSTPAID_DEACTIVATIONS",
    "NUM_POSTPAID_LINES", 
    "NUM_POSTPAID_SERVICES", 
    "NUM_TOTAL_POSTPAID_LINES",
    "MB_TOTAL", 
    "SECONDS_INCOMING_CALL_OWN_NETWORK", 
    "INVOICING_TOTAL_WITHOUT_TAXES",
    "SECONDS_OUTGOING_CALL_OWN_NETWORK", 
    "DAYS_FIRST_ACCOUNT", 
    "MOBILE_CALL_MINUTES",
    "KPI_TAXES",
    "NUM_FIXED_DEACTIVATIONS",
    "NUM_DEACTIVATIONS",
    "PERCENTAGE_SECONDS_OWN_NETWORK",
    "INVOICING_TERM"
  ))
}


preprocess_data <- function(data) {
  data <- impute_median(data) 
  data <- remove_unwanted_columns(data) 
  return(data)
}


mobile_train_cleaned <- preprocess_data(mobile_train)
mobile_test_cleaned <- preprocess_data(mobile_test)

GLM model development

We will now fit a Generalized Linear Model (GLM) from the binomial family because the response variable is binary. This means the target outcome has two possible categories. The binomial family is appropriate for modeling probabilities of such binary outcomes. Additionally, the logit link function is used, which transforms the predicted probabilities into log-odds, allowing the model to capture the relationship between the predictors and the log-odds of the target event.

First model

The first model includes the next variables: INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES, AGE and MONTHLY_MB.

The chi-squared statistic is 625.289, with a p-value of 0.000, indicating that the model significantly improves over a null model with no predictors. The modelâs Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) is 17978.919.

The model includes a statistically significant intercept with an estimate of -0.613. This value represents the log-odds of the dependent variable (the probability of making a purchase) being equal to 1 when all predictor variables are zero. A negative intercept suggests that the baseline probability of the event occurring is below 50%.

The variable INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES has a positive estimated coefficient of 0.010. This implies that for every unit increase in invoicing total taxes, the log-odds of the dependent variable being 1 increase by 0.010. In simpler terms, higher invoicing total taxes are associated with an increased probability of the event occurring. This relationship is highly significant (p < 0.001), highlighting the strong contribution of this variable to the model.

For AGE, the estimated coefficient is -0.016, which indicates a negative relationship between age and the probability of the event. Specifically, for every additional year of age, the log-odds of the event decrease by 0.016, meaning that older individuals are less likely to exhibit the event (e.g., make a purchase). This effect is also highly significant (p < 0.001), demonstrating that age is a key predictor in the model.

Lastly, the variable MONTHLY_MB shows a positive estimated coefficient of approximately 0.000. While the effect size is small, it suggests a positive relationship between monthly data usage and the probability of the event. This means that even slight increases in data usage are associated with a higher likelihood of the event occurring. The variableâs significance (p < 0.001) underscores its importance in the model, despite the small magnitude of its effect.

To better see the effects of the variables, some graphs are displayed.

  • Graph 1: This graph shows that as the total invoicing amount increases, the predicted probability of the customer making a purchase in the next month also rises. The relationship appears to be nonlinear, resembling an S-shaped curve, which is typical in logistic models.

  • Graph 2: This graph indicates that the probability of making a purchase decreases as the customerâs age increases. The relationship seems to be linear and negative, suggesting a consistent decline in purchase probability with age.

  • Graph 3: This graph demonstrates that as monthly data usage increases, the probability of making a purchase also increases. The relationship is quite similar to that of INVOICING_TOTAL_TAXES, likely because both variables reflect customer behaviour in terms of usage patterns. The shaded blue region represents the uncertainty interval (confidence band) around the predicted probabilities. At the extreme values of MONTHLY_MB (both very low and very high), the confidence band is narrower, indicating that the modelâs predictions are more certain in these ranges. This pattern suggests that the model has greater confidence in the probabilities it predicts when monthly data usage is either minimal or very high.

Now, predictions are made using the test dataset to evaluate the modelâs performance. In addition to assessing the model with the AIC (Akaike Information Criterion), further evaluation metrics are used, including the AUC (Area Under the Curve) and the ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) curve. The AUC measures the modelâs ability to distinguish between the two classes, with a value closer to 1 indicating better discrimination. The ROC curve graphically represents this performance by plotting the True Positive Rate (Sensitivity) against the False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity) at various threshold levels.

mobile_test_cleaned$predicted_prob <- predict(glm_base, newdata = mobile_test_cleaned, type = "response")
mobile_test_cleaned$predicted_class <- ifelse(mobile_test_cleaned$predicted_prob > 0.5, 1, 0)
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(as.factor(mobile_test_cleaned$predicted_class), 
                               as.factor(mobile_test_cleaned$TARGET))

roc_curve <- roc(mobile_test_cleaned$TARGET, mobile_test_cleaned$predicted_prob)
auc_value <- auc(roc_curve)

roc_data <- data.frame(
  TPR = rev(roc_curve$sensitivities),  
  FPR = rev(1 - roc_curve$specificities)
)

ggplot(roc_data, aes(x = FPR, y = TPR)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +

The calculated AUC (Area Under the Curve) is 0.652, indicating that the model has a moderate ability to discriminate between the two classes. An AUC of 0.652 means that, on average, the model correctly distinguishes between a randomly chosen positive and negative case 65.2% of the time.

To provide a baseline for comparison, a benchmark model was created using only the intercept, with no predictors or interactions. This establishes a minimal baseline against which the predictive power and improvements of all subsequent models can be measured.

All models significantly outperformed the benchmark model, as evidenced by higher AUC, lower AIC, and improved metrics like balanced accuracy. This demonstrates the added value of incorporating predictors and interactions in explaining and predicting customer behaviour.

Each successive model showed incremental improvements in metrics such as AUC, balanced accuracy, and specificity. The final model exhibited the best performance, with the lowest AIC and the highest AUC, balanced accuracy, and specificity.

Across all models, ZONE_FIXED_PENETRATION emerged as the most influential predictor, highlighting the importance of regional fixed-line penetration. Other key factors included NUM_MAIN_POSTPAID_LINES and INVOICING_QUOTA, demonstrating their relevance in explaining customer purchasing behaviour.
